            <fr:display-uri>idem-comm-59IF</fr:display-uri>
            <fr:route>/idem-comm-59IF/</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Set-level duality between spectra and algebra">Set-level duality between spectra and algebra</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Proposition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p>
  For any map <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f : D \to  E]]></fr:tex> between distributive lattices:
  <html:ol><html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is injective iff <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} E \twoheadrightarrow  \operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex> is surjective.</html:li>
    <html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is surjective iff <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} E \subseteq  \operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex> is a full subposet.</html:li>
    <html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is an epimorphism iff <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} E \to  \operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex> is injective. (There is also an <fr:link href="/idem-comm-VEWK/" title="Epimorphisms between distributive lattices" uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-VEWK/" display-uri="idem-comm-VEWK" type="local">algebraic description</fr:link> of epimorphisms between distributive lattices.) </html:li></html:ol></html:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors /><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>7</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  <html:p>
    (1) is an easy consequence of completeness.
  </html:p>
  <html:p>
    For (2), since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec}]]></fr:tex> takes regular epis in <html:strong>DL</html:strong> to regular monos in <html:strong>Pos</html:strong>, thus the only if direction holds. For the if direction, take a map <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f : D \to  E]]></fr:tex>, we can factor it as a surjection <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q : D \twoheadrightarrow  E']]></fr:tex> followed by an injection <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i : E' \rightarrowtail  E]]></fr:tex>. This induces a factorisation on posets <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q : \operatorname {Spec} E' \to  \operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex>, a regular mono, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i : \operatorname {Spec} E \to  \operatorname {Spec} E']]></fr:tex>, which is surjective by (1). Hence, if the composite <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[iq]]></fr:tex> is a regular mono, so is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i]]></fr:tex>, which implies <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i]]></fr:tex> is an isomorphism. This way, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> must be a quotient.
  </html:p>
  <html:p>
    For (3), this follows from monomorphisms of spectral spaces are exact injective ones.
  </html:p>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
